2102/// X86_64ABIInfo - The X86_64 ABI information.
2103class X86_64ABIInfo : public SwiftABIInfo {
2104 enum Class {
2105 Integer = 0,
2106 SSE,
2107 SSEUp,
2108 X87,
2109 X87Up,
2110 ComplexX87,
2111 NoClass,
2112 Memory
2113 };
2114
2115 /// merge - Implement the X86_64 ABI merging algorithm.
2116 ///
2117 /// Merge an accumulating classification \arg Accum with a field
2118 /// classification \arg Field.
2119 ///
2120 /// \param Accum - The accumulating classification. This should
2121 /// always be either NoClass or the result of a previous merge
2122 /// call. In addition, this should never be Memory (the caller
2123 /// should just return Memory for the aggregate).
2124 static Class merge(Class Accum, Class Field);
2125
2126 /// postMerge - Implement the X86_64 ABI post merging algorithm.
2127 ///
2128 /// Post merger cleanup, reduces a malformed Hi and Lo pair to
2129 /// final MEMORY or SSE classes when necessary.
2130 ///
2131 /// \param AggregateSize - The size of the current aggregate in
2132 /// the classification process.
2133 ///
2134 /// \param Lo - The classification for the parts of the type
2135 /// residing in the low word of the containing object.
2136 ///
2137 /// \param Hi - The classification for the parts of the type
2138 /// residing in the higher words of the containing object.
2139 ///
2140 void postMerge(unsigned AggregateSize, Class &Lo, Class &Hi) const;
2141
2142 /// classify - Determine the x86_64 register classes in which the
2143 /// given type T should be passed.
2144 ///
2145 /// \param Lo - The classification for the parts of the type
2146 /// residing in the low word of the containing object.
2147 ///
2148 /// \param Hi - The classification for the parts of the type
2149 /// residing in the high word of the containing object.
2150 ///
2151 /// \param OffsetBase - The bit offset of this type in the
2152 /// containing object. Some parameters are classified different
2153 /// depending on whether they straddle an eightbyte boundary.
2154 ///
2155 /// \param isNamedArg - Whether the argument in question is a "named"
2156 /// argument, as used in AMD64-ABI 3.5.7.
2157 ///
2158 /// If a word is unused its result will be NoClass; if a type should
2159 /// be passed in Memory then at least the classification of \arg Lo
2160 /// will be Memory.
2161 ///
2162 /// The \arg Lo class will be NoClass iff the argument is ignored.
2163 ///
2164 /// If the \arg Lo class is ComplexX87, then the \arg Hi class will
2165 /// also be ComplexX87.
2166 void classify(QualType T, uint64_t OffsetBase, Class &Lo, Class &Hi,
2167 bool isNamedArg) const;
2168
2169 llvm::Type *GetByteVectorType(QualType Ty) const;
2170 llvm::Type *GetSSETypeAtOffset(llvm::Type *IRType,
2171 unsigned IROffset, QualType SourceTy,
2172 unsigned SourceOffset) const;
2173 llvm::Type *GetINTEGERTypeAtOffset(llvm::Type *IRType,
2174 unsigned IROffset, QualType SourceTy,
2175 unsigned SourceOffset) const;
2176
2177 /// getIndirectResult - Give a source type \arg Ty, return a suitable result
2178 /// such that the argument will be returned in memory.
2179 ABIArgInfo getIndirectReturnResult(QualType Ty) const;
2180
2181 /// getIndirectResult - Give a source type \arg Ty, return a suitable result
2182 /// such that the argument will be passed in memory.
2183 ///
2184 /// \param freeIntRegs - The number of free integer registers remaining
2185 /// available.
2186 ABIArgInfo getIndirectResult(QualType Ty, unsigned freeIntRegs) const;
2187
2188 ABIArgInfo classifyReturnType(QualType RetTy) const;
2189
2190 ABIArgInfo classifyArgumentType(QualType Ty, unsigned freeIntRegs,
2191 unsigned &neededInt, unsigned &neededSSE,
2192 bool isNamedArg) const;
2193
2194 ABIArgInfo classifyRegCallStructType(QualType Ty, unsigned &NeededInt,
2195 unsigned &NeededSSE) const;
2196
2197 ABIArgInfo classifyRegCallStructTypeImpl(QualType Ty, unsigned &NeededInt,
2198 unsigned &NeededSSE) const;
2199
2200 bool IsIllegalVectorType(QualType Ty) const;
2201
2202 /// The 0.98 ABI revision clarified a lot of ambiguities,
2203 /// unfortunately in ways that were not always consistent with
2204 /// certain previous compilers. In particular, platforms which
2205 /// required strict binary compatibility with older versions of GCC
2206 /// may need to exempt themselves.
2207 bool honorsRevision0_98() const {
2208 return !getTarget().getTriple().isOSDarwin();
2209 }
2210
2211 /// GCC classifies <1 x long long> as SSE but some platform ABIs choose to
2212 /// classify it as INTEGER (for compatibility with older clang compilers).
2213 bool classifyIntegerMMXAsSSE() const {
2214 // Clang <= 3.8 did not do this.
2215 if (getContext().getLangOpts().getClangABICompat() <=
2216 LangOptions::ClangABI::Ver3_8)
2217 return false;
2218
2219 const llvm::Triple &Triple = getTarget().getTriple();
2220 if (Triple.isOSDarwin() || Triple.getOS() == llvm::Triple::PS4)
2221 return false;
2222 if (Triple.isOSFreeBSD() && Triple.getOSMajorVersion() >= 10)
2223 return false;
2224 return true;
2225 }
2226
2227 X86AVXABILevel AVXLevel;
2228 // Some ABIs (e.g. X32 ABI and Native Client OS) use 32 bit pointers on
2229 // 64-bit hardware.
2230 bool Has64BitPointers;
2231
2232public:
2233 X86_64ABIInfo(CodeGen::CodeGenTypes &CGT, X86AVXABILevel AVXLevel) :
2234 SwiftABIInfo(CGT), AVXLevel(AVXLevel),
2235 Has64BitPointers(CGT.getDataLayout().getPointerSize(0) == 8) {
2236 }
2237
2238 bool isPassedUsingAVXType(QualType type) const {
2239 unsigned neededInt, neededSSE;
2240 // The freeIntRegs argument doesn't matter here.
2241 ABIArgInfo info = classifyArgumentType(type, 0, neededInt, neededSSE,
2242 /*isNamedArg*/true);
2243 if (info.isDirect()) {
2244 llvm::Type *ty = info.getCoerceToType();
2245 if (llvm::VectorType *vectorTy = dyn_cast_or_null<llvm::VectorType>(ty))
2246 return (vectorTy->getBitWidth() > 128);
2247 }
2248 return false;
2249 }
2250
2251 void computeInfo(CGFunctionInfo &FI) const override;
2252
2253 Address EmitVAArg(CodeGenFunction &CGF, Address VAListAddr,
2254 QualType Ty) const override;
2255 Address EmitMSVAArg(CodeGenFunction &CGF, Address VAListAddr,
2256 QualType Ty) const override;
2257
2258 bool has64BitPointers() const {
2259 return Has64BitPointers;
2260 }
2261
2262 bool shouldPassIndirectlyForSwift(ArrayRef<llvm::Type*> scalars,
2263 bool asReturnValue) const override {
2264 return occupiesMoreThan(CGT, scalars, /*total*/ 4);
2265 }
2266 bool isSwiftErrorInRegister() const override {
2267 return true;
2268 }
2269};
2270
2271/// WinX86_64ABIInfo - The Windows X86_64 ABI information.
2272class WinX86_64ABIInfo : public SwiftABIInfo {
2273public:
2274 WinX86_64ABIInfo(CodeGen::CodeGenTypes &CGT)
2275 : SwiftABIInfo(CGT),
2276 IsMingw64(getTarget().getTriple().isWindowsGNUEnvironment()) {}
2277
2278 void computeInfo(CGFunctionInfo &FI) const override;
2279
2280 Address EmitVAArg(CodeGenFunction &CGF, Address VAListAddr,
2281 QualType Ty) const override;
2282
2283 bool isHomogeneousAggregateBaseType(QualType Ty) const override {
2284 // FIXME: Assumes vectorcall is in use.
2285 return isX86VectorTypeForVectorCall(getContext(), Ty);
2286 }
2287
2288 bool isHomogeneousAggregateSmallEnough(const Type *Ty,
2289 uint64_t NumMembers) const override {
2290 // FIXME: Assumes vectorcall is in use.
2291 return isX86VectorCallAggregateSmallEnough(NumMembers);
2292 }
2293
2294 bool shouldPassIndirectlyForSwift(ArrayRef<llvm::Type *> scalars,
2295 bool asReturnValue) const override {
2296 return occupiesMoreThan(CGT, scalars, /*total*/ 4);
2297 }
2298
2299 bool isSwiftErrorInRegister() const override {
2300 return true;
2301 }
2302
2303private:
2304 ABIArgInfo classify(QualType Ty, unsigned &FreeSSERegs, bool IsReturnType,
2305 bool IsVectorCall, bool IsRegCall) const;
2306 ABIArgInfo reclassifyHvaArgType(QualType Ty, unsigned &FreeSSERegs,
2307 const ABIArgInfo &current) const;
2308 void computeVectorCallArgs(CGFunctionInfo &FI, unsigned FreeSSERegs,
2309 bool IsVectorCall, bool IsRegCall) const;
2310
2311 bool IsMingw64;
2312};

2314class X86_64TargetCodeGenInfo : public TargetCodeGenInfo {
2315public:
2316 X86_64TargetCodeGenInfo(CodeGen::CodeGenTypes &CGT, X86AVXABILevel AVXLevel)
2317 : TargetCodeGenInfo(new X86_64ABIInfo(CGT, AVXLevel)) {}
2318
2319 const X86_64ABIInfo &getABIInfo() const {
2320 return static_cast<const X86_64ABIInfo&>(TargetCodeGenInfo::getABIInfo());
2321 }
2322
2323 /// Disable tail call on x86-64. The epilogue code before the tail jump blocks
2324 /// the autoreleaseRV/retainRV optimization.
2325 bool shouldSuppressTailCallsOfRetainAutoreleasedReturnValue() const override {
2326 return true;
2327 }
2328
2329 int getDwarfEHStackPointer(CodeGen::CodeGenModule &CGM) const override {
2330 return 7;
2331 }
2332
2333 bool initDwarfEHRegSizeTable(CodeGen::CodeGenFunction &CGF,
2334 llvm::Value *Address) const override {
2335 llvm::Value *Eight8 = llvm::ConstantInt::get(CGF.Int8Ty, 8);
2336
2337 // 0-15 are the 16 integer registers.
2338 // 16 is %rip.
2339 AssignToArrayRange(CGF.Builder, Address, Eight8, 0, 16);
2340 return false;
2341 }
2342
2343 llvm::Type* adjustInlineAsmType(CodeGen::CodeGenFunction &CGF,
2344 StringRef Constraint,
2345 llvm::Type* Ty) const override {
2346 return X86AdjustInlineAsmType(CGF, Constraint, Ty);
2347 }
2348
2349 bool isNoProtoCallVariadic(const CallArgList &args,
2350 const FunctionNoProtoType *fnType) const override {
2351 // The default CC on x86-64 sets %al to the number of SSA
2352 // registers used, and GCC sets this when calling an unprototyped
2353 // function, so we override the default behavior. However, don't do
2354 // that when AVX types are involved: the ABI explicitly states it is
2355 // undefined, and it doesn't work in practice because of how the ABI
2356 // defines varargs anyway.
2357 if (fnType->getCallConv() == CC_C) {
2358 bool HasAVXType = false;
2359 for (CallArgList::const_iterator
2360 it = args.begin(), ie = args.end(); it != ie; ++it) {
2361 if (getABIInfo().isPassedUsingAVXType(it->Ty)) {
2362 HasAVXType = true;
2363 break;
2364 }
2365 }
2366
2367 if (!HasAVXType)
2368 return true;
2369 }
2370
2371 return TargetCodeGenInfo::isNoProtoCallVariadic(args, fnType);
2372 }
2373
2374 llvm::Constant *
2375 getUBSanFunctionSignature(CodeGen::CodeGenModule &CGM) const override {
2376 unsigned Sig = (0xeb << 0) | // jmp rel8
2377 (0x06 << 8) | // .+0x08
2378 ('v' << 16) |
2379 ('2' << 24);
2380 return llvm::ConstantInt::get(CGM.Int32Ty, Sig);
2381 }
2382
2383 void setTargetAttributes(const Decl *D, llvm::GlobalValue *GV,
2384 CodeGen::CodeGenModule &CGM) const override {
2385 if (GV->isDeclaration())
2386 return;
2387 if (const FunctionDecl *FD = dyn_cast_or_null<FunctionDecl>(D)) {
2388 if (FD->hasAttr<X86ForceAlignArgPointerAttr>()) {
2389 llvm::Function *Fn = cast<llvm::Function>(GV);
2390 Fn->addFnAttr("stackrealign");
2391 }
2392 if (FD->hasAttr<AnyX86InterruptAttr>()) {
2393 llvm::Function *Fn = cast<llvm::Function>(GV);
2394 Fn->setCallingConv(llvm::CallingConv::X86_INTR);
2395 }
2396 }
2397 }
2398};

2400static std::string qualifyWindowsLibrary(llvm::StringRef Lib) {
2401 // If the argument does not end in .lib, automatically add the suffix.
2402 // If the argument contains a space, enclose it in quotes.
2403 // This matches the behavior of MSVC.
2404 bool Quote = (Lib.find(" ") != StringRef::npos);
2405 std::string ArgStr = Quote ? "\"" : "";
2406 ArgStr += Lib;
2407 if (!Lib.endswith_lower(".lib") && !Lib.endswith_lower(".a"))
2408 ArgStr += ".lib";
2409 ArgStr += Quote ? "\"" : "";
2410 return ArgStr;
2411}

2437static void addStackProbeTargetAttributes(const Decl *D, llvm::GlobalValue *GV,
2438 CodeGen::CodeGenModule &CGM) {
2439 if (llvm::Function *Fn = dyn_cast_or_null<llvm::Function>(GV)) {
2440
2441 if (CGM.getCodeGenOpts().StackProbeSize != 4096)
2442 Fn->addFnAttr("stack-probe-size",
2443 llvm::utostr(CGM.getCodeGenOpts().StackProbeSize));
2444 if (CGM.getCodeGenOpts().NoStackArgProbe)
2445 Fn->addFnAttr("no-stack-arg-probe");
2446 }
2447}

2511}
2512
2513void X86_64ABIInfo::postMerge(unsigned AggregateSize, Class &Lo,
2514 Class &Hi) const {
2515 // AMD64-ABI 3.2.3p2: Rule 5. Then a post merger cleanup is done:
2516 //
2517 // (a) If one of the classes is Memory, the whole argument is passed in
2518 // memory.
2519 //
2520 // (b) If X87UP is not preceded by X87, the whole argument is passed in
2521 // memory.
2522 //
2523 // (c) If the size of the aggregate exceeds two eightbytes and the first
2524 // eightbyte isn't SSE or any other eightbyte isn't SSEUP, the whole
2525 // argument is passed in memory. NOTE: This is necessary to keep the
2526 // ABI working for processors that don't support the __m256 type.
2527 //
2528 // (d) If SSEUP is not preceded by SSE or SSEUP, it is converted to SSE.
2529 //
2530 // Some of these are enforced by the merging logic. Others can arise
2531 // only with unions; for example:
2532 // union { _Complex double; unsigned; }
2533 //
2534 // Note that clauses (b) and (c) were added in 0.98.
2535 //
2536 if (Hi == Memory)
2537 Lo = Memory;
2538 if (Hi == X87Up && Lo != X87 && honorsRevision0_98())
2539 Lo = Memory;
2540 if (AggregateSize > 128 && (Lo != SSE || Hi != SSEUp))
2541 Lo = Memory;
2542 if (Hi == SSEUp && Lo != SSE)
2543 Hi = SSE;
2544}
2545
2546X86_64ABIInfo::Class X86_64ABIInfo::merge(Class Accum, Class Field) {
2547 // AMD64-ABI 3.2.3p2: Rule 4. Each field of an object is
2548 // classified recursively so that always two fields are
2549 // considered. The resulting class is calculated according to
2550 // the classes of the fields in the eightbyte:
2551 //
2552 // (a) If both classes are equal, this is the resulting class.
2553 //
2554 // (b) If one of the classes is NO_CLASS, the resulting class is
2555 // the other class.
2556 //
2557 // (c) If one of the classes is MEMORY, the result is the MEMORY
2558 // class.
2559 //
2560 // (d) If one of the classes is INTEGER, the result is the
2561 // INTEGER.
2562 //
2563 // (e) If one of the classes is X87, X87UP, COMPLEX_X87 class,
2564 // MEMORY is used as class.
2565 //
2566 // (f) Otherwise class SSE is used.
2567
2568 // Accum should never be memory (we should have returned) or
2569 // ComplexX87 (because this cannot be passed in a structure).
2570 assert((Accum != Memory && Accum != ComplexX87) &&
2571 "Invalid accumulated classification during merge.");
2572 if (Accum == Field || Field == NoClass)
2573 return Accum;
2574 if (Field == Memory)
2575 return Memory;
2576 if (Accum == NoClass)
2577 return Field;
2578 if (Accum == Integer || Field == Integer)
2579 return Integer;
2580 if (Field == X87 || Field == X87Up || Field == ComplexX87 ||
2581 Accum == X87 || Accum == X87Up)
2582 return Memory;
2583 return SSE;
2584}
2585
2586void X86_64ABIInfo::classify(QualType Ty, uint64_t OffsetBase,
2587 Class &Lo, Class &Hi, bool isNamedArg) const {
2588 // FIXME: This code can be simplified by introducing a simple value class for
2589 // Class pairs with appropriate constructor methods for the various
2590 // situations.
2591
2592 // FIXME: Some of the split computations are wrong; unaligned vectors
2593 // shouldn't be passed in registers for example, so there is no chance they
2594 // can straddle an eightbyte. Verify & simplify.
2595
2596 Lo = Hi = NoClass;
2597
2598 Class &Current = OffsetBase < 64 ? Lo : Hi;
2599 Current = Memory;
2600
2601 if (const BuiltinType *BT = Ty->getAs<BuiltinType>()) {
2602 BuiltinType::Kind k = BT->getKind();
2603
2604 if (k == BuiltinType::Void) {
2605 Current = NoClass;
2606 } else if (k == BuiltinType::Int128 || k == BuiltinType::UInt128) {
2607 Lo = Integer;
2608 Hi = Integer;
2609 } else if (k >= BuiltinType::Bool && k <= BuiltinType::LongLong) {
2610 Current = Integer;
2611 } else if (k == BuiltinType::Float || k == BuiltinType::Double) {
2612 Current = SSE;
2613 } else if (k == BuiltinType::LongDouble) {
2614 const llvm::fltSemantics *LDF = &getTarget().getLongDoubleFormat();
2615 if (LDF == &llvm::APFloat::IEEEquad()) {
2616 Lo = SSE;
2617 Hi = SSEUp;
2618 } else if (LDF == &llvm::APFloat::x87DoubleExtended()) {
2619 Lo = X87;
2620 Hi = X87Up;
2621 } else if (LDF == &llvm::APFloat::IEEEdouble()) {
2622 Current = SSE;
2623 } else
2624 llvm_unreachable("unexpected long double representation!");
2625 }
2626 // FIXME: _Decimal32 and _Decimal64 are SSE.
2627 // FIXME: _float128 and _Decimal128 are (SSE, SSEUp).
2628 return;
2629 }
2630
2631 if (const EnumType *ET = Ty->getAs<EnumType>()) {
2632 // Classify the underlying integer type.
2633 classify(ET->getDecl()->getIntegerType(), OffsetBase, Lo, Hi, isNamedArg);
2634 return;
2635 }
2636
2637 if (Ty->hasPointerRepresentation()) {
2638 Current = Integer;
2639 return;
2640 }
2641
2642 if (Ty->isMemberPointerType()) {
2643 if (Ty->isMemberFunctionPointerType()) {
2644 if (Has64BitPointers) {
2645 // If Has64BitPointers, this is an {i64, i64}, so classify both
2646 // Lo and Hi now.
2647 Lo = Hi = Integer;
2648 } else {
2649 // Otherwise, with 32-bit pointers, this is an {i32, i32}. If that
2650 // straddles an eightbyte boundary, Hi should be classified as well.
2651 uint64_t EB_FuncPtr = (OffsetBase) / 64;
2652 uint64_t EB_ThisAdj = (OffsetBase + 64 - 1) / 64;
2653 if (EB_FuncPtr != EB_ThisAdj) {
2654 Lo = Hi = Integer;
2655 } else {
2656 Current = Integer;
2657 }
2658 }
2659 } else {
2660 Current = Integer;
2661 }
2662 return;
2663 }
2664
2665 if (const VectorType *VT = Ty->getAs<VectorType>()) {
2666 uint64_t Size = getContext().getTypeSize(VT);
2667 if (Size == 1 || Size == 8 || Size == 16 || Size == 32) {
2668 // gcc passes the following as integer:
2669 // 4 bytes - <4 x char>, <2 x short>, <1 x int>, <1 x float>
2670 // 2 bytes - <2 x char>, <1 x short>
2671 // 1 byte - <1 x char>
2672 Current = Integer;
2673
2674 // If this type crosses an eightbyte boundary, it should be
2675 // split.
2676 uint64_t EB_Lo = (OffsetBase) / 64;
2677 uint64_t EB_Hi = (OffsetBase + Size - 1) / 64;
2678 if (EB_Lo != EB_Hi)
2679 Hi = Lo;
2680 } else if (Size == 64) {
2681 QualType ElementType = VT->getElementType();
2682
2683 // gcc passes <1 x double> in memory. :(
2684 if (ElementType->isSpecificBuiltinType(BuiltinType::Double))
2685 return;
2686
2687 // gcc passes <1 x long long> as SSE but clang used to unconditionally
2688 // pass them as integer. For platforms where clang is the de facto
2689 // platform compiler, we must continue to use integer.
2690 if (!classifyIntegerMMXAsSSE() &&
2691 (ElementType->isSpecificBuiltinType(BuiltinType::LongLong) ||
2692 ElementType->isSpecificBuiltinType(BuiltinType::ULongLong) ||
2693 ElementType->isSpecificBuiltinType(BuiltinType::Long) ||
2694 ElementType->isSpecificBuiltinType(BuiltinType::ULong)))
2695 Current = Integer;
2696 else
2697 Current = SSE;
2698
2699 // If this type crosses an eightbyte boundary, it should be
2700 // split.
2701 if (OffsetBase && OffsetBase != 64)
2702 Hi = Lo;
2703 } else if (Size == 128 ||
2704 (isNamedArg && Size <= getNativeVectorSizeForAVXABI(AVXLevel))) {
2705 // Arguments of 256-bits are split into four eightbyte chunks. The
2706 // least significant one belongs to class SSE and all the others to class
2707 // SSEUP. The original Lo and Hi design considers that types can't be
2708 // greater than 128-bits, so a 64-bit split in Hi and Lo makes sense.
2709 // This design isn't correct for 256-bits, but since there're no cases
2710 // where the upper parts would need to be inspected, avoid adding
2711 // complexity and just consider Hi to match the 64-256 part.
2712 //
2713 // Note that per 3.5.7 of AMD64-ABI, 256-bit args are only passed in
2714 // registers if they are "named", i.e. not part of the "..." of a
2715 // variadic function.
2716 //
2717 // Similarly, per 3.2.3. of the AVX512 draft, 512-bits ("named") args are
2718 // split into eight eightbyte chunks, one SSE and seven SSEUP.
2719 Lo = SSE;
2720 Hi = SSEUp;
2721 }
2722 return;
2723 }
2724
2725 if (const ComplexType *CT = Ty->getAs<ComplexType>()) {
2726 QualType ET = getContext().getCanonicalType(CT->getElementType());
2727
2728 uint64_t Size = getContext().getTypeSize(Ty);
2729 if (ET->isIntegralOrEnumerationType()) {
2730 if (Size <= 64)
2731 Current = Integer;
2732 else if (Size <= 128)
2733 Lo = Hi = Integer;
2734 } else if (ET == getContext().FloatTy) {
2735 Current = SSE;
2736 } else if (ET == getContext().DoubleTy) {
2737 Lo = Hi = SSE;
2738 } else if (ET == getContext().LongDoubleTy) {
2739 const llvm::fltSemantics *LDF = &getTarget().getLongDoubleFormat();
2740 if (LDF == &llvm::APFloat::IEEEquad())
2741 Current = Memory;
2742 else if (LDF == &llvm::APFloat::x87DoubleExtended())
2743 Current = ComplexX87;
2744 else if (LDF == &llvm::APFloat::IEEEdouble())
2745 Lo = Hi = SSE;
2746 else
2747 llvm_unreachable("unexpected long double representation!");
2748 }
2749
2750 // If this complex type crosses an eightbyte boundary then it
2751 // should be split.
2752 uint64_t EB_Real = (OffsetBase) / 64;
2753 uint64_t EB_Imag = (OffsetBase + getContext().getTypeSize(ET)) / 64;
2754 if (Hi == NoClass && EB_Real != EB_Imag)
2755 Hi = Lo;
2756
2757 return;
2758 }
2759
2760 if (const ConstantArrayType *AT = getContext().getAsConstantArrayType(Ty)) {
2761 // Arrays are treated like structures.
2762
2763 uint64_t Size = getContext().getTypeSize(Ty);
2764
2765 // AMD64-ABI 3.2.3p2: Rule 1. If the size of an object is larger
2766 // than eight eightbytes, ..., it has class MEMORY.
2767 if (Size > 512)
2768 return;
2769
2770 // AMD64-ABI 3.2.3p2: Rule 1. If ..., or it contains unaligned
2771 // fields, it has class MEMORY.
2772 //
2773 // Only need to check alignment of array base.
2774 if (OffsetBase % getContext().getTypeAlign(AT->getElementType()))
2775 return;
2776
2777 // Otherwise implement simplified merge. We could be smarter about
2778 // this, but it isn't worth it and would be harder to verify.
2779 Current = NoClass;
2780 uint64_t EltSize = getContext().getTypeSize(AT->getElementType());
2781 uint64_t ArraySize = AT->getSize().getZExtValue();
2782
2783 // The only case a 256-bit wide vector could be used is when the array
2784 // contains a single 256-bit element. Since Lo and Hi logic isn't extended
2785 // to work for sizes wider than 128, early check and fallback to memory.
2786 //
2787 if (Size > 128 &&
2788 (Size != EltSize || Size > getNativeVectorSizeForAVXABI(AVXLevel)))
2789 return;
2790
2791 for (uint64_t i=0, Offset=OffsetBase; i<ArraySize; ++i, Offset += EltSize) {
2792 Class FieldLo, FieldHi;
2793 classify(AT->getElementType(), Offset, FieldLo, FieldHi, isNamedArg);
2794 Lo = merge(Lo, FieldLo);
2795 Hi = merge(Hi, FieldHi);
2796 if (Lo == Memory || Hi == Memory)
2797 break;
2798 }
2799
2800 postMerge(Size, Lo, Hi);
2801 assert((Hi != SSEUp || Lo == SSE) && "Invalid SSEUp array classification.");
2802 return;
2803 }
2804
2805 if (const RecordType *RT = Ty->getAs<RecordType>()) {
2806 uint64_t Size = getContext().getTypeSize(Ty);
2807
2808 // AMD64-ABI 3.2.3p2: Rule 1. If the size of an object is larger
2809 // than eight eightbytes, ..., it has class MEMORY.
2810 if (Size > 512)
2811 return;
2812
2813 // AMD64-ABI 3.2.3p2: Rule 2. If a C++ object has either a non-trivial
2814 // copy constructor or a non-trivial destructor, it is passed by invisible
2815 // reference.
2816 if (getRecordArgABI(RT, getCXXABI()))
2817 return;
2818
2819 const RecordDecl *RD = RT->getDecl();
2820
2821 // Assume variable sized types are passed in memory.
2822 if (RD->hasFlexibleArrayMember())
2823 return;
2824
2825 const ASTRecordLayout &Layout = getContext().getASTRecordLayout(RD);
2826
2827 // Reset Lo class, this will be recomputed.
2828 Current = NoClass;
2829
2830 // If this is a C++ record, classify the bases first.
2831 if (const CXXRecordDecl *CXXRD = dyn_cast<CXXRecordDecl>(RD)) {
2832 for (const auto &I : CXXRD->bases()) {
2833 assert(!I.isVirtual() && !I.getType()->isDependentType() &&
2834 "Unexpected base class!");
2835 const CXXRecordDecl *Base =
2836 cast<CXXRecordDecl>(I.getType()->getAs<RecordType>()->getDecl());
2837
2838 // Classify this field.
2839 //
2840 // AMD64-ABI 3.2.3p2: Rule 3. If the size of the aggregate exceeds a
2841 // single eightbyte, each is classified separately. Each eightbyte gets
2842 // initialized to class NO_CLASS.
2843 Class FieldLo, FieldHi;
2844 uint64_t Offset =
2845 OffsetBase + getContext().toBits(Layout.getBaseClassOffset(Base));
2846 classify(I.getType(), Offset, FieldLo, FieldHi, isNamedArg);
2847 Lo = merge(Lo, FieldLo);
2848 Hi = merge(Hi, FieldHi);
2849 if (Lo == Memory || Hi == Memory) {
2850 postMerge(Size, Lo, Hi);
2851 return;
2852 }
2853 }
2854 }
2855
2856 // Classify the fields one at a time, merging the results.
2857 unsigned idx = 0;
2858 for (RecordDecl::field_iterator i = RD->field_begin(), e = RD->field_end();
2859 i != e; ++i, ++idx) {
2860 uint64_t Offset = OffsetBase + Layout.getFieldOffset(idx);
2861 bool BitField = i->isBitField();
2862
2863 // Ignore padding bit-fields.
2864 if (BitField && i->isUnnamedBitfield())
2865 continue;
2866
2867 // AMD64-ABI 3.2.3p2: Rule 1. If the size of an object is larger than
2868 // four eightbytes, or it contains unaligned fields, it has class MEMORY.
2869 //
2870 // The only case a 256-bit wide vector could be used is when the struct
2871 // contains a single 256-bit element. Since Lo and Hi logic isn't extended
2872 // to work for sizes wider than 128, early check and fallback to memory.
2873 //
2874 if (Size > 128 && (Size != getContext().getTypeSize(i->getType()) ||
2875 Size > getNativeVectorSizeForAVXABI(AVXLevel))) {
2876 Lo = Memory;
2877 postMerge(Size, Lo, Hi);
2878 return;
2879 }
2880 // Note, skip this test for bit-fields, see below.
2881 if (!BitField && Offset % getContext().getTypeAlign(i->getType())) {
2882 Lo = Memory;
2883 postMerge(Size, Lo, Hi);
2884 return;
2885 }
2886
2887 // Classify this field.
2888 //
2889 // AMD64-ABI 3.2.3p2: Rule 3. If the size of the aggregate
2890 // exceeds a single eightbyte, each is classified
2891 // separately. Each eightbyte gets initialized to class
2892 // NO_CLASS.
2893 Class FieldLo, FieldHi;
2894
2895 // Bit-fields require special handling, they do not force the
2896 // structure to be passed in memory even if unaligned, and
2897 // therefore they can straddle an eightbyte.
2898 if (BitField) {
2899 assert(!i->isUnnamedBitfield());
2900 uint64_t Offset = OffsetBase + Layout.getFieldOffset(idx);
2901 uint64_t Size = i->getBitWidthValue(getContext());
2902
2903 uint64_t EB_Lo = Offset / 64;
2904 uint64_t EB_Hi = (Offset + Size - 1) / 64;
2905
2906 if (EB_Lo) {
2907 assert(EB_Hi == EB_Lo && "Invalid classification, type > 16 bytes.");
2908 FieldLo = NoClass;
2909 FieldHi = Integer;
2910 } else {
2911 FieldLo = Integer;
2912 FieldHi = EB_Hi ? Integer : NoClass;
2913 }
2914 } else
2915 classify(i->getType(), Offset, FieldLo, FieldHi, isNamedArg);
2916 Lo = merge(Lo, FieldLo);
2917 Hi = merge(Hi, FieldHi);
2918 if (Lo == Memory || Hi == Memory)
2919 break;
2920 }
2921
2922 postMerge(Size, Lo, Hi);
2923 }
2924}
2925
2926ABIArgInfo X86_64ABIInfo::getIndirectReturnResult(QualType Ty) const {
2927 // If this is a scalar LLVM value then assume LLVM will pass it in the right
2928 // place naturally.
2929 if (!isAggregateTypeForABI(Ty)) {
2930 // Treat an enum type as its underlying type.
2931 if (const EnumType *EnumTy = Ty->getAs<EnumType>())
2932 Ty = EnumTy->getDecl()->getIntegerType();
2933
2934 return (Ty->isPromotableIntegerType() ? ABIArgInfo::getExtend(Ty)
2935 : ABIArgInfo::getDirect());
2936 }
2937
2938 return getNaturalAlignIndirect(Ty);
2939}
2940
2941bool X86_64ABIInfo::IsIllegalVectorType(QualType Ty) const {
2942 if (const VectorType *VecTy = Ty->getAs<VectorType>()) {
2943 uint64_t Size = getContext().getTypeSize(VecTy);
2944 unsigned LargestVector = getNativeVectorSizeForAVXABI(AVXLevel);
2945 if (Size <= 64 || Size > LargestVector)
2946 return true;
2947 }
2948
2949 return false;
2950}
2951
2952ABIArgInfo X86_64ABIInfo::getIndirectResult(QualType Ty,
2953 unsigned freeIntRegs) const {
2954 // If this is a scalar LLVM value then assume LLVM will pass it in the right
2955 // place naturally.
2956 //
2957 // This assumption is optimistic, as there could be free registers available
2958 // when we need to pass this argument in memory, and LLVM could try to pass
2959 // the argument in the free register. This does not seem to happen currently,
2960 // but this code would be much safer if we could mark the argument with
2961 // 'onstack'. See PR12193.
2962 if (!isAggregateTypeForABI(Ty) && !IsIllegalVectorType(Ty)) {
2963 // Treat an enum type as its underlying type.
2964 if (const EnumType *EnumTy = Ty->getAs<EnumType>())
2965 Ty = EnumTy->getDecl()->getIntegerType();
2966
2967 return (Ty->isPromotableIntegerType() ? ABIArgInfo::getExtend(Ty)
2968 : ABIArgInfo::getDirect());
2969 }
2970
2971 if (CGCXXABI::RecordArgABI RAA = getRecordArgABI(Ty, getCXXABI()))
2972 return getNaturalAlignIndirect(Ty, RAA == CGCXXABI::RAA_DirectInMemory);
2973
2974 // Compute the byval alignment. We specify the alignment of the byval in all
2975 // cases so that the mid-level optimizer knows the alignment of the byval.
2976 unsigned Align = std::max(getContext().getTypeAlign(Ty) / 8, 8U);
2977
2978 // Attempt to avoid passing indirect results using byval when possible. This
2979 // is important for good codegen.
2980 //
2981 // We do this by coercing the value into a scalar type which the backend can
2982 // handle naturally (i.e., without using byval).
2983 //
2984 // For simplicity, we currently only do this when we have exhausted all of the
2985 // free integer registers. Doing this when there are free integer registers
2986 // would require more care, as we would have to ensure that the coerced value
2987 // did not claim the unused register. That would require either reording the
2988 // arguments to the function (so that any subsequent inreg values came first),
2989 // or only doing this optimization when there were no following arguments that
2990 // might be inreg.
2991 //
2992 // We currently expect it to be rare (particularly in well written code) for
2993 // arguments to be passed on the stack when there are still free integer
2994 // registers available (this would typically imply large structs being passed
2995 // by value), so this seems like a fair tradeoff for now.
2996 //
2997 // We can revisit this if the backend grows support for 'onstack' parameter
2998 // attributes. See PR12193.
2999 if (freeIntRegs == 0) {
3000 uint64_t Size = getContext().getTypeSize(Ty);
3001
3002 // If this type fits in an eightbyte, coerce it into the matching integral
3003 // type, which will end up on the stack (with alignment 8).
3004 if (Align == 8 && Size <= 64)
3005 return ABIArgInfo::getDirect(llvm::IntegerType::get(getVMContext(),
3006 Size));
3007 }
3008
3009 return ABIArgInfo::getIndirect(CharUnits::fromQuantity(Align));
3010}
3011
3012/// The ABI specifies that a value should be passed in a full vector XMM/YMM
3013/// register. Pick an LLVM IR type that will be passed as a vector register.
3014llvm::Type *X86_64ABIInfo::GetByteVectorType(QualType Ty) const {
3015 // Wrapper structs/arrays that only contain vectors are passed just like
3016 // vectors; strip them off if present.
3017 if (const Type *InnerTy = isSingleElementStruct(Ty, getContext()))
3018 Ty = QualType(InnerTy, 0);
3019
3020 llvm::Type *IRType = CGT.ConvertType(Ty);
3021 if (isa<llvm::VectorType>(IRType) ||
3022 IRType->getTypeID() == llvm::Type::FP128TyID)
3023 return IRType;
3024
3025 // We couldn't find the preferred IR vector type for 'Ty'.
3026 uint64_t Size = getContext().getTypeSize(Ty);
3027 assert((Size == 128 || Size == 256 || Size == 512) && "Invalid type found!");
3028
3029 // Return a LLVM IR vector type based on the size of 'Ty'.
3030 return llvm::VectorType::get(llvm::Type::getDoubleTy(getVMContext()),
3031 Size / 64);
3032}
3033
3034/// BitsContainNoUserData - Return true if the specified [start,end) bit range
3035/// is known to either be off the end of the specified type or being in
3036/// alignment padding. The user type specified is known to be at most 128 bits
3037/// in size, and have passed through X86_64ABIInfo::classify with a successful
3038/// classification that put one of the two halves in the INTEGER class.
3039///
3040/// It is conservatively correct to return false.
3041static bool BitsContainNoUserData(QualType Ty, unsigned StartBit,
3042 unsigned EndBit, ASTContext &Context) {
3043 // If the bytes being queried are off the end of the type, there is no user
3044 // data hiding here. This handles analysis of builtins, vectors and other
3045 // types that don't contain interesting padding.
3046 unsigned TySize = (unsigned)Context.getTypeSize(Ty);
3047 if (TySize <= StartBit)
3048 return true;
3049
3050 if (const ConstantArrayType *AT = Context.getAsConstantArrayType(Ty)) {
3051 unsigned EltSize = (unsigned)Context.getTypeSize(AT->getElementType());
3052 unsigned NumElts = (unsigned)AT->getSize().getZExtValue();
3053
3054 // Check each element to see if the element overlaps with the queried range.
3055 for (unsigned i = 0; i != NumElts; ++i) {
3056 // If the element is after the span we care about, then we're done..
3057 unsigned EltOffset = i*EltSize;
3058 if (EltOffset >= EndBit) break;
3059
3060 unsigned EltStart = EltOffset < StartBit ? StartBit-EltOffset :0;
3061 if (!BitsContainNoUserData(AT->getElementType(), EltStart,
3062 EndBit-EltOffset, Context))
3063 return false;
3064 }
3065 // If it overlaps no elements, then it is safe to process as padding.
3066 return true;
3067 }
3068
3069 if (const RecordType *RT = Ty->getAs<RecordType>()) {
3070 const RecordDecl *RD = RT->getDecl();
3071 const ASTRecordLayout &Layout = Context.getASTRecordLayout(RD);
3072
3073 // If this is a C++ record, check the bases first.
3074 if (const CXXRecordDecl *CXXRD = dyn_cast<CXXRecordDecl>(RD)) {
3075 for (const auto &I : CXXRD->bases()) {
3076 assert(!I.isVirtual() && !I.getType()->isDependentType() &&
3077 "Unexpected base class!");
3078 const CXXRecordDecl *Base =
3079 cast<CXXRecordDecl>(I.getType()->getAs<RecordType>()->getDecl());
3080
3081 // If the base is after the span we care about, ignore it.
3082 unsigned BaseOffset = Context.toBits(Layout.getBaseClassOffset(Base));
3083 if (BaseOffset >= EndBit) continue;
3084
3085 unsigned BaseStart = BaseOffset < StartBit ? StartBit-BaseOffset :0;
3086 if (!BitsContainNoUserData(I.getType(), BaseStart,
3087 EndBit-BaseOffset, Context))
3088 return false;
3089 }
3090 }
3091
3092 // Verify that no field has data that overlaps the region of interest. Yes
3093 // this could be sped up a lot by being smarter about queried fields,
3094 // however we're only looking at structs up to 16 bytes, so we don't care
3095 // much.
3096 unsigned idx = 0;
3097 for (RecordDecl::field_iterator i = RD->field_begin(), e = RD->field_end();
3098 i != e; ++i, ++idx) {
3099 unsigned FieldOffset = (unsigned)Layout.getFieldOffset(idx);
3100
3101 // If we found a field after the region we care about, then we're done.
3102 if (FieldOffset >= EndBit) break;
3103
3104 unsigned FieldStart = FieldOffset < StartBit ? StartBit-FieldOffset :0;
3105 if (!BitsContainNoUserData(i->getType(), FieldStart, EndBit-FieldOffset,
3106 Context))
3107 return false;
3108 }
3109
3110 // If nothing in this record overlapped the area of interest, then we're
3111 // clean.
3112 return true;
3113 }
3114
3115 return false;
3116}
3117
3118/// ContainsFloatAtOffset - Return true if the specified LLVM IR type has a
3119/// float member at the specified offset. For example, {int,{float}} has a
3120/// float at offset 4. It is conservatively correct for this routine to return
3121/// false.
3122static bool ContainsFloatAtOffset(llvm::Type *IRType, unsigned IROffset,
3123 const llvm::DataLayout &TD) {
3124 // Base case if we find a float.
3125 if (IROffset == 0 && IRType->isFloatTy())
3126 return true;
3127
3128 // If this is a struct, recurse into the field at the specified offset.
3129 if (llvm::StructType *STy = dyn_cast<llvm::StructType>(IRType)) {
3130 const llvm::StructLayout *SL = TD.getStructLayout(STy);
3131 unsigned Elt = SL->getElementContainingOffset(IROffset);
3132 IROffset -= SL->getElementOffset(Elt);
3133 return ContainsFloatAtOffset(STy->getElementType(Elt), IROffset, TD);
3134 }
3135
3136 // If this is an array, recurse into the field at the specified offset.
3137 if (llvm::ArrayType *ATy = dyn_cast<llvm::ArrayType>(IRType)) {
3138 llvm::Type *EltTy = ATy->getElementType();
3139 unsigned EltSize = TD.getTypeAllocSize(EltTy);
3140 IROffset -= IROffset/EltSize*EltSize;
3141 return ContainsFloatAtOffset(EltTy, IROffset, TD);
3142 }
3143
3144 return false;
3145}
3146
3147
3148/// GetSSETypeAtOffset - Return a type that will be passed by the backend in the
3149/// low 8 bytes of an XMM register, corresponding to the SSE class.
3150llvm::Type *X86_64ABIInfo::
3151GetSSETypeAtOffset(llvm::Type *IRType, unsigned IROffset,
3152 QualType SourceTy, unsigned SourceOffset) const {
3153 // The only three choices we have are either double, <2 x float>, or float. We
3154 // pass as float if the last 4 bytes is just padding. This happens for
3155 // structs that contain 3 floats.
3156 if (BitsContainNoUserData(SourceTy, SourceOffset*8+32,
3157 SourceOffset*8+64, getContext()))
3158 return llvm::Type::getFloatTy(getVMContext());
3159
3160 // We want to pass as <2 x float> if the LLVM IR type contains a float at
3161 // offset+0 and offset+4. Walk the LLVM IR type to find out if this is the
3162 // case.
3163 if (ContainsFloatAtOffset(IRType, IROffset, getDataLayout()) &&
3164 ContainsFloatAtOffset(IRType, IROffset+4, getDataLayout()))
3165 return llvm::VectorType::get(llvm::Type::getFloatTy(getVMContext()), 2);
3166
3167 return llvm::Type::getDoubleTy(getVMContext());
3168}
3169
3170
3171/// GetINTEGERTypeAtOffset - The ABI specifies that a value should be passed in
3172/// an 8-byte GPR. This means that we either have a scalar or we are talking
3173/// about the high or low part of an up-to-16-byte struct. This routine picks
3174/// the best LLVM IR type to represent this, which may be i64 or may be anything
3175/// else that the backend will pass in a GPR that works better (e.g. i8, %foo*,
3176/// etc).
3177///
3178/// PrefType is an LLVM IR type that corresponds to (part of) the IR type for
3179/// the source type. IROffset is an offset in bytes into the LLVM IR type that
3180/// the 8-byte value references. PrefType may be null.
3181///
3182/// SourceTy is the source-level type for the entire argument. SourceOffset is
3183/// an offset into this that we're processing (which is always either 0 or 8).
3184///
3185llvm::Type *X86_64ABIInfo::
3186GetINTEGERTypeAtOffset(llvm::Type *IRType, unsigned IROffset,
3187 QualType SourceTy, unsigned SourceOffset) const {
3188 // If we're dealing with an un-offset LLVM IR type, then it means that we're
3189 // returning an 8-byte unit starting with it. See if we can safely use it.
3190 if (IROffset == 0) {
3191 // Pointers and int64's always fill the 8-byte unit.
3192 if ((isa<llvm::PointerType>(IRType) && Has64BitPointers) ||
3193 IRType->isIntegerTy(64))
3194 return IRType;
3195
3196 // If we have a 1/2/4-byte integer, we can use it only if the rest of the
3197 // goodness in the source type is just tail padding. This is allowed to
3198 // kick in for struct {double,int} on the int, but not on
3199 // struct{double,int,int} because we wouldn't return the second int. We
3200 // have to do this analysis on the source type because we can't depend on
3201 // unions being lowered a specific way etc.
3202 if (IRType->isIntegerTy(8) || IRType->isIntegerTy(16) ||
3203 IRType->isIntegerTy(32) ||
3204 (isa<llvm::PointerType>(IRType) && !Has64BitPointers)) {
3205 unsigned BitWidth = isa<llvm::PointerType>(IRType) ? 32 :
3206 cast<llvm::IntegerType>(IRType)->getBitWidth();
3207
3208 if (BitsContainNoUserData(SourceTy, SourceOffset*8+BitWidth,
3209 SourceOffset*8+64, getContext()))
3210 return IRType;
3211 }
3212 }
3213
3214 if (llvm::StructType *STy = dyn_cast<llvm::StructType>(IRType)) {
3215 // If this is a struct, recurse into the field at the specified offset.
3216 const llvm::StructLayout *SL = getDataLayout().getStructLayout(STy);
3217 if (IROffset < SL->getSizeInBytes()) {
3218 unsigned FieldIdx = SL->getElementContainingOffset(IROffset);
3219 IROffset -= SL->getElementOffset(FieldIdx);
3220
3221 return GetINTEGERTypeAtOffset(STy->getElementType(FieldIdx), IROffset,
3222 SourceTy, SourceOffset);
3223 }
3224 }
3225
3226 if (llvm::ArrayType *ATy = dyn_cast<llvm::ArrayType>(IRType)) {
3227 llvm::Type *EltTy = ATy->getElementType();
3228 unsigned EltSize = getDataLayout().getTypeAllocSize(EltTy);
3229 unsigned EltOffset = IROffset/EltSize*EltSize;
3230 return GetINTEGERTypeAtOffset(EltTy, IROffset-EltOffset, SourceTy,
3231 SourceOffset);
3232 }
3233
3234 // Okay, we don't have any better idea of what to pass, so we pass this in an
3235 // integer register that isn't too big to fit the rest of the struct.
3236 unsigned TySizeInBytes =
3237 (unsigned)getContext().getTypeSizeInChars(SourceTy).getQuantity();
3238
3239 assert(TySizeInBytes != SourceOffset && "Empty field?");
3240
3241 // It is always safe to classify this as an integer type up to i64 that
3242 // isn't larger than the structure.
3243 return llvm::IntegerType::get(getVMContext(),
3244 std::min(TySizeInBytes-SourceOffset, 8U)*8);
3245}
3246
3247
3248/// GetX86_64ByValArgumentPair - Given a high and low type that can ideally
3249/// be used as elements of a two register pair to pass or return, return a
3250/// first class aggregate to represent them. For example, if the low part of
3251/// a by-value argument should be passed as i32* and the high part as float,
3252/// return {i32*, float}.
3253static llvm::Type *
3254GetX86_64ByValArgumentPair(llvm::Type *Lo, llvm::Type *Hi,
3255 const llvm::DataLayout &TD) {
3256 // In order to correctly satisfy the ABI, we need to the high part to start
3257 // at offset 8. If the high and low parts we inferred are both 4-byte types
3258 // (e.g. i32 and i32) then the resultant struct type ({i32,i32}) won't have
3259 // the second element at offset 8. Check for this:
3260 unsigned LoSize = (unsigned)TD.getTypeAllocSize(Lo);
3261 unsigned HiAlign = TD.getABITypeAlignment(Hi);
3262 unsigned HiStart = llvm::alignTo(LoSize, HiAlign);
3263 assert(HiStart != 0 && HiStart <= 8 && "Invalid x86-64 argument pair!");
3264
3265 // To handle this, we have to increase the size of the low part so that the
3266 // second element will start at an 8 byte offset. We can't increase the size
3267 // of the second element because it might make us access off the end of the
3268 // struct.
3269 if (HiStart != 8) {
3270 // There are usually two sorts of types the ABI generation code can produce
3271 // for the low part of a pair that aren't 8 bytes in size: float or
3272 // i8/i16/i32. This can also include pointers when they are 32-bit (X32 and
3273 // NaCl).
3274 // Promote these to a larger type.
3275 if (Lo->isFloatTy())
3276 Lo = llvm::Type::getDoubleTy(Lo->getContext());
3277 else {
3278 assert((Lo->isIntegerTy() || Lo->isPointerTy())
3279 && "Invalid/unknown lo type");
3280 Lo = llvm::Type::getInt64Ty(Lo->getContext());
3281 }
3282 }
3283
3284 llvm::StructType *Result = llvm::StructType::get(Lo, Hi);
3285
3286 // Verify that the second element is at an 8-byte offset.
3287 assert(TD.getStructLayout(Result)->getElementOffset(1) == 8 &&
3288 "Invalid x86-64 argument pair!");
3289 return Result;
3290}
3291
3292ABIArgInfo X86_64ABIInfo::
3293classifyReturnType(QualType RetTy) const {
3294 // AMD64-ABI 3.2.3p4: Rule 1. Classify the return type with the
3295 // classification algorithm.
3296 X86_64ABIInfo::Class Lo, Hi;
3297 classify(RetTy, 0, Lo, Hi, /*isNamedArg*/ true);
3298
3299 // Check some invariants.
3300 assert((Hi != Memory || Lo == Memory) && "Invalid memory classification.");
3301 assert((Hi != SSEUp || Lo == SSE) && "Invalid SSEUp classification.");
3302
3303 llvm::Type *ResType = nullptr;
3304 switch (Lo) {
3305 case NoClass:
3306 if (Hi == NoClass)
3307 return ABIArgInfo::getIgnore();
3308 // If the low part is just padding, it takes no register, leave ResType
3309 // null.
3310 assert((Hi == SSE || Hi == Integer || Hi == X87Up) &&
3311 "Unknown missing lo part");
3312 break;
3313
3314 case SSEUp:
3315 case X87Up:
3316 llvm_unreachable("Invalid classification for lo word.");
3317
3318 // AMD64-ABI 3.2.3p4: Rule 2. Types of class memory are returned via
3319 // hidden argument.
3320 case Memory:
3321 return getIndirectReturnResult(RetTy);
3322
3323 // AMD64-ABI 3.2.3p4: Rule 3. If the class is INTEGER, the next
3324 // available register of the sequence %rax, %rdx is used.
3325 case Integer:
3326 ResType = GetINTEGERTypeAtOffset(CGT.ConvertType(RetTy), 0, RetTy, 0);
3327
3328 // If we have a sign or zero extended integer, make sure to return Extend
3329 // so that the parameter gets the right LLVM IR attributes.
3330 if (Hi == NoClass && isa<llvm::IntegerType>(ResType)) {
3331 // Treat an enum type as its underlying type.
3332 if (const EnumType *EnumTy = RetTy->getAs<EnumType>())
3333 RetTy = EnumTy->getDecl()->getIntegerType();
3334
3335 if (RetTy->isIntegralOrEnumerationType() &&
3336 RetTy->isPromotableIntegerType())
3337 return ABIArgInfo::getExtend(RetTy);
3338 }
3339 break;
3340
3341 // AMD64-ABI 3.2.3p4: Rule 4. If the class is SSE, the next
3342 // available SSE register of the sequence %xmm0, %xmm1 is used.
3343 case SSE:
3344 ResType = GetSSETypeAtOffset(CGT.ConvertType(RetTy), 0, RetTy, 0);
3345 break;
3346
3347 // AMD64-ABI 3.2.3p4: Rule 6. If the class is X87, the value is
3348 // returned on the X87 stack in %st0 as 80-bit x87 number.
3349 case X87:
3350 ResType = llvm::Type::getX86_FP80Ty(getVMContext());
3351 break;
3352
3353 // AMD64-ABI 3.2.3p4: Rule 8. If the class is COMPLEX_X87, the real
3354 // part of the value is returned in %st0 and the imaginary part in
3355 // %st1.
3356 case ComplexX87:
3357 assert(Hi == ComplexX87 && "Unexpected ComplexX87 classification.");
3358 ResType = llvm::StructType::get(llvm::Type::getX86_FP80Ty(getVMContext()),
3359 llvm::Type::getX86_FP80Ty(getVMContext()));
3360 break;
3361 }
3362
3363 llvm::Type *HighPart = nullptr;
3364 switch (Hi) {
3365 // Memory was handled previously and X87 should
3366 // never occur as a hi class.
3367 case Memory:
3368 case X87:
3369 llvm_unreachable("Invalid classification for hi word.");
3370
3371 case ComplexX87: // Previously handled.
3372 case NoClass:
3373 break;
3374
3375 case Integer:
3376 HighPart = GetINTEGERTypeAtOffset(CGT.ConvertType(RetTy), 8, RetTy, 8);
3377 if (Lo == NoClass) // Return HighPart at offset 8 in memory.
3378 return ABIArgInfo::getDirect(HighPart, 8);
3379 break;
3380 case SSE:
3381 HighPart = GetSSETypeAtOffset(CGT.ConvertType(RetTy), 8, RetTy, 8);
3382 if (Lo == NoClass) // Return HighPart at offset 8 in memory.
3383 return ABIArgInfo::getDirect(HighPart, 8);
3384 break;
3385
3386 // AMD64-ABI 3.2.3p4: Rule 5. If the class is SSEUP, the eightbyte
3387 // is passed in the next available eightbyte chunk if the last used
3388 // vector register.
3389 //
3390 // SSEUP should always be preceded by SSE, just widen.
3391 case SSEUp:
3392 assert(Lo == SSE && "Unexpected SSEUp classification.");
3393 ResType = GetByteVectorType(RetTy);
3394 break;
3395
3396 // AMD64-ABI 3.2.3p4: Rule 7. If the class is X87UP, the value is
3397 // returned together with the previous X87 value in %st0.
3398 case X87Up:
3399 // If X87Up is preceded by X87, we don't need to do
3400 // anything. However, in some cases with unions it may not be
3401 // preceded by X87. In such situations we follow gcc and pass the
3402 // extra bits in an SSE reg.
3403 if (Lo != X87) {
3404 HighPart = GetSSETypeAtOffset(CGT.ConvertType(RetTy), 8, RetTy, 8);
3405 if (Lo == NoClass) // Return HighPart at offset 8 in memory.
3406 return ABIArgInfo::getDirect(HighPart, 8);
3407 }
3408 break;
3409 }
3410
3411 // If a high part was specified, merge it together with the low part. It is
3412 // known to pass in the high eightbyte of the result. We do this by forming a
3413 // first class struct aggregate with the high and low part: {low, high}
3414 if (HighPart)
3415 ResType = GetX86_64ByValArgumentPair(ResType, HighPart, getDataLayout());
3416
3417 return ABIArgInfo::getDirect(ResType);
3418}
3419
3420ABIArgInfo X86_64ABIInfo::classifyArgumentType(
3421 QualType Ty, unsigned freeIntRegs, unsigned &neededInt, unsigned &neededSSE,
3422 bool isNamedArg)
3423 const
3424{
3425 Ty = useFirstFieldIfTransparentUnion(Ty);
3426
3427 X86_64ABIInfo::Class Lo, Hi;
3428 classify(Ty, 0, Lo, Hi, isNamedArg);
3429
3430 // Check some invariants.
3431 // FIXME: Enforce these by construction.
3432 assert((Hi != Memory || Lo == Memory) && "Invalid memory classification.");
3433 assert((Hi != SSEUp || Lo == SSE) && "Invalid SSEUp classification.");
3434
3435 neededInt = 0;
3436 neededSSE = 0;
3437 llvm::Type *ResType = nullptr;
3438 switch (Lo) {
3439 case NoClass:
3440 if (Hi == NoClass)
3441 return ABIArgInfo::getIgnore();
3442 // If the low part is just padding, it takes no register, leave ResType
3443 // null.
3444 assert((Hi == SSE || Hi == Integer || Hi == X87Up) &&
3445 "Unknown missing lo part");
3446 break;
3447
3448 // AMD64-ABI 3.2.3p3: Rule 1. If the class is MEMORY, pass the argument
3449 // on the stack.
3450 case Memory:
3451
3452 // AMD64-ABI 3.2.3p3: Rule 5. If the class is X87, X87UP or
3453 // COMPLEX_X87, it is passed in memory.
3454 case X87:
3455 case ComplexX87:
3456 if (getRecordArgABI(Ty, getCXXABI()) == CGCXXABI::RAA_Indirect)
3457 ++neededInt;
3458 return getIndirectResult(Ty, freeIntRegs);
3459
3460 case SSEUp:
3461 case X87Up:
3462 llvm_unreachable("Invalid classification for lo word.");
3463
3464 // AMD64-ABI 3.2.3p3: Rule 2. If the class is INTEGER, the next
3465 // available register of the sequence %rdi, %rsi, %rdx, %rcx, %r8
3466 // and %r9 is used.
3467 case Integer:
3468 ++neededInt;
3469
3470 // Pick an 8-byte type based on the preferred type.
3471 ResType = GetINTEGERTypeAtOffset(CGT.ConvertType(Ty), 0, Ty, 0);
3472
3473 // If we have a sign or zero extended integer, make sure to return Extend
3474 // so that the parameter gets the right LLVM IR attributes.
3475 if (Hi == NoClass && isa<llvm::IntegerType>(ResType)) {
3476 // Treat an enum type as its underlying type.
3477 if (const EnumType *EnumTy = Ty->getAs<EnumType>())
3478 Ty = EnumTy->getDecl()->getIntegerType();
3479
3480 if (Ty->isIntegralOrEnumerationType() &&
3481 Ty->isPromotableIntegerType())
3482 return ABIArgInfo::getExtend(Ty);
3483 }
3484
3485 break;
3486
3487 // AMD64-ABI 3.2.3p3: Rule 3. If the class is SSE, the next
3488 // available SSE register is used, the registers are taken in the
3489 // order from %xmm0 to %xmm7.
3490 case SSE: {
3491 llvm::Type *IRType = CGT.ConvertType(Ty);
3492 ResType = GetSSETypeAtOffset(IRType, 0, Ty, 0);
3493 ++neededSSE;
3494 break;
3495 }
3496 }
3497
3498 llvm::Type *HighPart = nullptr;
3499 switch (Hi) {
3500 // Memory was handled previously, ComplexX87 and X87 should
3501 // never occur as hi classes, and X87Up must be preceded by X87,
3502 // which is passed in memory.
3503 case Memory:
3504 case X87:
3505 case ComplexX87:
3506 llvm_unreachable("Invalid classification for hi word.");
3507
3508 case NoClass: break;
3509
3510 case Integer:
3511 ++neededInt;
3512 // Pick an 8-byte type based on the preferred type.
3513 HighPart = GetINTEGERTypeAtOffset(CGT.ConvertType(Ty), 8, Ty, 8);
3514
3515 if (Lo == NoClass) // Pass HighPart at offset 8 in memory.
3516 return ABIArgInfo::getDirect(HighPart, 8);
3517 break;
3518
3519 // X87Up generally doesn't occur here (long double is passed in
3520 // memory), except in situations involving unions.
3521 case X87Up:
3522 case SSE:
3523 HighPart = GetSSETypeAtOffset(CGT.ConvertType(Ty), 8, Ty, 8);
3524
3525 if (Lo == NoClass) // Pass HighPart at offset 8 in memory.
3526 return ABIArgInfo::getDirect(HighPart, 8);
3527
3528 ++neededSSE;
3529 break;
3530
3531 // AMD64-ABI 3.2.3p3: Rule 4. If the class is SSEUP, the
3532 // eightbyte is passed in the upper half of the last used SSE
3533 // register. This only happens when 128-bit vectors are passed.
3534 case SSEUp:
3535 assert(Lo == SSE && "Unexpected SSEUp classification");
3536 ResType = GetByteVectorType(Ty);
3537 break;
3538 }
3539
3540 // If a high part was specified, merge it together with the low part. It is
3541 // known to pass in the high eightbyte of the result. We do this by forming a
3542 // first class struct aggregate with the high and low part: {low, high}
3543 if (HighPart)
3544 ResType = GetX86_64ByValArgumentPair(ResType, HighPart, getDataLayout());
3545
3546 return ABIArgInfo::getDirect(ResType);
3547}
3548
3549ABIArgInfo
3550X86_64ABIInfo::classifyRegCallStructTypeImpl(QualType Ty, unsigned &NeededInt,
3551 unsigned &NeededSSE) const {
3552 auto RT = Ty->getAs<RecordType>();
3553 assert(RT && "classifyRegCallStructType only valid with struct types");
3554
3555 if (RT->getDecl()->hasFlexibleArrayMember())
3556 return getIndirectReturnResult(Ty);
3557
3558 // Sum up bases
3559 if (auto CXXRD = dyn_cast<CXXRecordDecl>(RT->getDecl())) {
3560 if (CXXRD->isDynamicClass()) {
3561 NeededInt = NeededSSE = 0;
3562 return getIndirectReturnResult(Ty);
3563 }
3564
3565 for (const auto &I : CXXRD->bases())
3566 if (classifyRegCallStructTypeImpl(I.getType(), NeededInt, NeededSSE)
3567 .isIndirect()) {
3568 NeededInt = NeededSSE = 0;
3569 return getIndirectReturnResult(Ty);
3570 }
3571 }
3572
3573 // Sum up members
3574 for (const auto *FD : RT->getDecl()->fields()) {
3575 if (FD->getType()->isRecordType() && !FD->getType()->isUnionType()) {
3576 if (classifyRegCallStructTypeImpl(FD->getType(), NeededInt, NeededSSE)
3577 .isIndirect()) {
3578 NeededInt = NeededSSE = 0;
3579 return getIndirectReturnResult(Ty);
3580 }
3581 } else {
3582 unsigned LocalNeededInt, LocalNeededSSE;
3583 if (classifyArgumentType(FD->getType(), UINT_MAX, LocalNeededInt,
3584 LocalNeededSSE, true)
3585 .isIndirect()) {
3586 NeededInt = NeededSSE = 0;
3587 return getIndirectReturnResult(Ty);
3588 }
3589 NeededInt += LocalNeededInt;
3590 NeededSSE += LocalNeededSSE;
3591 }
3592 }
3593
3594 return ABIArgInfo::getDirect();
3595}
3596
3597ABIArgInfo X86_64ABIInfo::classifyRegCallStructType(QualType Ty,
3598 unsigned &NeededInt,
3599 unsigned &NeededSSE) const {
3600
3601 NeededInt = 0;
3602 NeededSSE = 0;
3603
3604 return classifyRegCallStructTypeImpl(Ty, NeededInt, NeededSSE);
3605}
3606
3607void X86_64ABIInfo::computeInfo(CGFunctionInfo &FI) const {
3608
3609 const unsigned CallingConv = FI.getCallingConvention();
3610 // It is possible to force Win64 calling convention on any x86_64 target by
3611 // using __attribute__((ms_abi)). In such case to correctly emit Win64
3612 // compatible code delegate this call to WinX86_64ABIInfo::computeInfo.
3613 if (CallingConv == llvm::CallingConv::Win64) {
3614 WinX86_64ABIInfo Win64ABIInfo(CGT);
3615 Win64ABIInfo.computeInfo(FI);
3616 return;
3617 }
3618
3619 bool IsRegCall = CallingConv == llvm::CallingConv::X86_RegCall;
3620
3621 // Keep track of the number of assigned registers.
3622 unsigned FreeIntRegs = IsRegCall ? 11 : 6;
3623 unsigned FreeSSERegs = IsRegCall ? 16 : 8;
3624 unsigned NeededInt, NeededSSE;
3625
3626 if (!::classifyReturnType(getCXXABI(), FI, *this)) {
3627 if (IsRegCall && FI.getReturnType()->getTypePtr()->isRecordType() &&
3628 !FI.getReturnType()->getTypePtr()->isUnionType()) {
3629 FI.getReturnInfo() =
3630 classifyRegCallStructType(FI.getReturnType(), NeededInt, NeededSSE);
3631 if (FreeIntRegs >= NeededInt && FreeSSERegs >= NeededSSE) {
3632 FreeIntRegs -= NeededInt;
3633 FreeSSERegs -= NeededSSE;
3634 } else {
3635 FI.getReturnInfo() = getIndirectReturnResult(FI.getReturnType());
3636 }
3637 } else if (IsRegCall && FI.getReturnType()->getAs<ComplexType>()) {
3638 // Complex Long Double Type is passed in Memory when Regcall
3639 // calling convention is used.
3640 const ComplexType *CT = FI.getReturnType()->getAs<ComplexType>();
3641 if (getContext().getCanonicalType(CT->getElementType()) ==
3642 getContext().LongDoubleTy)
3643 FI.getReturnInfo() = getIndirectReturnResult(FI.getReturnType());
3644 } else
3645 FI.getReturnInfo() = classifyReturnType(FI.getReturnType());
3646 }
3647
3648 // If the return value is indirect, then the hidden argument is consuming one
3649 // integer register.
3650 if (FI.getReturnInfo().isIndirect())
3651 --FreeIntRegs;
3652
3653 // The chain argument effectively gives us another free register.
3654 if (FI.isChainCall())
3655 ++FreeIntRegs;
3656
3657 unsigned NumRequiredArgs = FI.getNumRequiredArgs();
3658 // AMD64-ABI 3.2.3p3: Once arguments are classified, the registers
3659 // get assigned (in left-to-right order) for passing as follows...
3660 unsigned ArgNo = 0;
3661 for (CGFunctionInfo::arg_iterator it = FI.arg_begin(), ie = FI.arg_end();
3662 it != ie; ++it, ++ArgNo) {
3663 bool IsNamedArg = ArgNo < NumRequiredArgs;
3664
3665 if (IsRegCall && it->type->isStructureOrClassType())
3666 it->info = classifyRegCallStructType(it->type, NeededInt, NeededSSE);
3667 else
3668 it->info = classifyArgumentType(it->type, FreeIntRegs, NeededInt,
3669 NeededSSE, IsNamedArg);
3670
3671 // AMD64-ABI 3.2.3p3: If there are no registers available for any
3672 // eightbyte of an argument, the whole argument is passed on the
3673 // stack. If registers have already been assigned for some
3674 // eightbytes of such an argument, the assignments get reverted.
3675 if (FreeIntRegs >= NeededInt && FreeSSERegs >= NeededSSE) {
3676 FreeIntRegs -= NeededInt;
3677 FreeSSERegs -= NeededSSE;
3678 } else {
3679 it->info = getIndirectResult(it->type, FreeIntRegs);
3680 }
3681 }
3682}
3683
3684static Address EmitX86_64VAArgFromMemory(CodeGenFunction &CGF,
3685 Address VAListAddr, QualType Ty) {
3686 Address overflow_arg_area_p =
3687 CGF.Builder.CreateStructGEP(VAListAddr, 2, "overflow_arg_area_p");
3688 llvm::Value *overflow_arg_area =
3689 CGF.Builder.CreateLoad(overflow_arg_area_p, "overflow_arg_area");
3690
3691 // AMD64-ABI 3.5.7p5: Step 7. Align l->overflow_arg_area upwards to a 16
3692 // byte boundary if alignment needed by type exceeds 8 byte boundary.
3693 // It isn't stated explicitly in the standard, but in practice we use
3694 // alignment greater than 16 where necessary.
3695 CharUnits Align = CGF.getContext().getTypeAlignInChars(Ty);
3696 if (Align > CharUnits::fromQuantity(8)) {
3697 overflow_arg_area = emitRoundPointerUpToAlignment(CGF, overflow_arg_area,
3698 Align);
3699 }
3700
3701 // AMD64-ABI 3.5.7p5: Step 8. Fetch type from l->overflow_arg_area.
3702 llvm::Type *LTy = CGF.ConvertTypeForMem(Ty);
3703 llvm::Value *Res =
3704 CGF.Builder.CreateBitCast(overflow_arg_area,
3705 CGF.CGM.getPointerInDefaultAS(LTy));
3706
3707 // AMD64-ABI 3.5.7p5: Step 9. Set l->overflow_arg_area to:
3708 // l->overflow_arg_area + sizeof(type).
3709 // AMD64-ABI 3.5.7p5: Step 10. Align l->overflow_arg_area upwards to
3710 // an 8 byte boundary.
3711
3712 uint64_t SizeInBytes = (CGF.getContext().getTypeSize(Ty) + 7) / 8;
3713 llvm::Value *Offset =
3714 llvm::ConstantInt::get(CGF.Int32Ty, (SizeInBytes + 7) & ~7);
3715 overflow_arg_area = CGF.Builder.CreateGEP(overflow_arg_area, Offset,
3716 "overflow_arg_area.next");
3717 CGF.Builder.CreateStore(overflow_arg_area, overflow_arg_area_p);
3718
3719 // AMD64-ABI 3.5.7p5: Step 11. Return the fetched type.
3720 return Address(Res, Align);
3721}
3722
3723Address X86_64ABIInfo::EmitVAArg(CodeGenFunction &CGF, Address VAListAddr,
3724 QualType Ty) const {
3725 // Assume that va_list type is correct; should be pointer to LLVM type:
3726 // struct {
3727 // i32 gp_offset;
3728 // i32 fp_offset;
3729 // i8* overflow_arg_area;
3730 // i8* reg_save_area;
3731 // };
3732 unsigned neededInt, neededSSE;
3733
3734 Ty = getContext().getCanonicalType(Ty);
3735 ABIArgInfo AI = classifyArgumentType(Ty, 0, neededInt, neededSSE,
3736 /*isNamedArg*/false);
3737
3738 // AMD64-ABI 3.5.7p5: Step 1. Determine whether type may be passed
3739 // in the registers. If not go to step 7.
3740 if (!neededInt && !neededSSE)
3741 return EmitX86_64VAArgFromMemory(CGF, VAListAddr, Ty);
3742
3743 // AMD64-ABI 3.5.7p5: Step 2. Compute num_gp to hold the number of
3744 // general purpose registers needed to pass type and num_fp to hold
3745 // the number of floating point registers needed.
3746
3747 // AMD64-ABI 3.5.7p5: Step 3. Verify whether arguments fit into
3748 // registers. In the case: l->gp_offset > 48 - num_gp * 8 or
3749 // l->fp_offset > 304 - num_fp * 16 go to step 7.
3750 //
3751 // NOTE: 304 is a typo, there are (6 * 8 + 8 * 16) = 176 bytes of
3752 // register save space).
3753
3754 llvm::Value *InRegs = nullptr;
3755 Address gp_offset_p = Address::invalid(), fp_offset_p = Address::invalid();
3756 llvm::Value *gp_offset = nullptr, *fp_offset = nullptr;
3757 if (neededInt) {
3758 gp_offset_p = CGF.Builder.CreateStructGEP(VAListAddr, 0, "gp_offset_p");
3759 gp_offset = CGF.Builder.CreateLoad(gp_offset_p, "gp_offset");
3760 InRegs = llvm::ConstantInt::get(CGF.Int32Ty, 48 - neededInt * 8);
3761 InRegs = CGF.Builder.CreateICmpULE(gp_offset, InRegs, "fits_in_gp");
3762 }
3763
3764 if (neededSSE) {
3765 fp_offset_p = CGF.Builder.CreateStructGEP(VAListAddr, 1, "fp_offset_p");
3766 fp_offset = CGF.Builder.CreateLoad(fp_offset_p, "fp_offset");
3767 llvm::Value *FitsInFP =
3768 llvm::ConstantInt::get(CGF.Int32Ty, 176 - neededSSE * 16);
3769 FitsInFP = CGF.Builder.CreateICmpULE(fp_offset, FitsInFP, "fits_in_fp");
3770 InRegs = InRegs ? CGF.Builder.CreateAnd(InRegs, FitsInFP) : FitsInFP;
3771 }
3772
3773 llvm::BasicBlock *InRegBlock = CGF.createBasicBlock("vaarg.in_reg");
3774 llvm::BasicBlock *InMemBlock = CGF.createBasicBlock("vaarg.in_mem");
3775 llvm::BasicBlock *ContBlock = CGF.createBasicBlock("vaarg.end");
3776 CGF.Builder.CreateCondBr(InRegs, InRegBlock, InMemBlock);
3777
3778 // Emit code to load the value if it was passed in registers.
3779
3780 CGF.EmitBlock(InRegBlock);
3781
3782 // AMD64-ABI 3.5.7p5: Step 4. Fetch type from l->reg_save_area with
3783 // an offset of l->gp_offset and/or l->fp_offset. This may require
3784 // copying to a temporary location in case the parameter is passed
3785 // in different register classes or requires an alignment greater
3786 // than 8 for general purpose registers and 16 for XMM registers.
3787 //
3788 // FIXME: This really results in shameful code when we end up needing to
3789 // collect arguments from different places; often what should result in a
3790 // simple assembling of a structure from scattered addresses has many more
3791 // loads than necessary. Can we clean this up?
3792 llvm::Type *LTy = CGF.ConvertTypeForMem(Ty);
3793 llvm::Value *RegSaveArea = CGF.Builder.CreateLoad(
3794 CGF.Builder.CreateStructGEP(VAListAddr, 3), "reg_save_area");
3795
3796 Address RegAddr = Address::invalid();
3797 if (neededInt && neededSSE) {
3798 // FIXME: Cleanup.
3799 assert(AI.isDirect() && "Unexpected ABI info for mixed regs");
3800 llvm::StructType *ST = cast<llvm::StructType>(AI.getCoerceToType());
3801 Address Tmp = CGF.CreateMemTemp(Ty);
3802 Tmp = CGF.Builder.CreateElementBitCast(Tmp, ST);
3803 assert(ST->getNumElements() == 2 && "Unexpected ABI info for mixed regs");
3804 llvm::Type *TyLo = ST->getElementType(0);
3805 llvm::Type *TyHi = ST->getElementType(1);
3806 assert((TyLo->isFPOrFPVectorTy() ^ TyHi->isFPOrFPVectorTy()) &&
3807 "Unexpected ABI info for mixed regs");
3808 llvm::Type *PTyLo = CGF.CGM.getPointerInDefaultAS(TyLo);
3809 llvm::Type *PTyHi = CGF.CGM.getPointerInDefaultAS(TyHi);
3810 llvm::Value *GPAddr = CGF.Builder.CreateGEP(RegSaveArea, gp_offset);
3811 llvm::Value *FPAddr = CGF.Builder.CreateGEP(RegSaveArea, fp_offset);
3812 llvm::Value *RegLoAddr = TyLo->isFPOrFPVectorTy() ? FPAddr : GPAddr;
3813 llvm::Value *RegHiAddr = TyLo->isFPOrFPVectorTy() ? GPAddr : FPAddr;
3814
3815 // Copy the first element.
3816 // FIXME: Our choice of alignment here and below is probably pessimistic.
3817 llvm::Value *V = CGF.Builder.CreateAlignedLoad(
3818 TyLo, CGF.Builder.CreateBitCast(RegLoAddr, PTyLo),
3819 CharUnits::fromQuantity(getDataLayout().getABITypeAlignment(TyLo)));
3820 CGF.Builder.CreateStore(V, CGF.Builder.CreateStructGEP(Tmp, 0));
3821
3822 // Copy the second element.
3823 V = CGF.Builder.CreateAlignedLoad(
3824 TyHi, CGF.Builder.CreateBitCast(RegHiAddr, PTyHi),
3825 CharUnits::fromQuantity(getDataLayout().getABITypeAlignment(TyHi)));
3826 CGF.Builder.CreateStore(V, CGF.Builder.CreateStructGEP(Tmp, 1));
3827
3828 RegAddr = CGF.Builder.CreateElementBitCast(Tmp, LTy);
3829 } else if (neededInt) {
3830 RegAddr = Address(CGF.Builder.CreateGEP(RegSaveArea, gp_offset),
3831 CharUnits::fromQuantity(8));
3832 RegAddr = CGF.Builder.CreateElementBitCast(RegAddr, LTy);
3833
3834 // Copy to a temporary if necessary to ensure the appropriate alignment.
3835 std::pair<CharUnits, CharUnits> SizeAlign =
3836 getContext().getTypeInfoInChars(Ty);
3837 uint64_t TySize = SizeAlign.first.getQuantity();
3838 CharUnits TyAlign = SizeAlign.second;
3839
3840 // Copy into a temporary if the type is more aligned than the
3841 // register save area.
3842 if (TyAlign.getQuantity() > 8) {
3843 Address Tmp = CGF.CreateMemTemp(Ty);
3844 CGF.Builder.CreateMemCpy(Tmp, RegAddr, TySize, false);
3845 RegAddr = Tmp;
3846 }
3847
3848 } else if (neededSSE == 1) {
3849 RegAddr = Address(CGF.Builder.CreateGEP(RegSaveArea, fp_offset),
3850 CharUnits::fromQuantity(16));
3851 RegAddr = CGF.Builder.CreateElementBitCast(RegAddr, LTy);
3852 } else {
3853 assert(neededSSE == 2 && "Invalid number of needed registers!");
3854 // SSE registers are spaced 16 bytes apart in the register save
3855 // area, we need to collect the two eightbytes together.
3856 // The ABI isn't explicit about this, but it seems reasonable
3857 // to assume that the slots are 16-byte aligned, since the stack is
3858 // naturally 16-byte aligned and the prologue is expected to store
3859 // all the SSE registers to the RSA.
3860 Address RegAddrLo = Address(CGF.Builder.CreateGEP(RegSaveArea, fp_offset),
3861 CharUnits::fromQuantity(16));
3862 Address RegAddrHi =
3863 CGF.Builder.CreateConstInBoundsByteGEP(RegAddrLo,
3864 CharUnits::fromQuantity(16));
3865 llvm::Type *ST = AI.canHaveCoerceToType()
3866 ? AI.getCoerceToType()
3867 : llvm::StructType::get(CGF.DoubleTy, CGF.DoubleTy);
3868 llvm::Value *V;
3869 Address Tmp = CGF.CreateMemTemp(Ty);
3870 Tmp = CGF.Builder.CreateElementBitCast(Tmp, ST);
3871 V = CGF.Builder.CreateLoad(CGF.Builder.CreateElementBitCast(
3872 RegAddrLo, ST->getStructElementType(0)));
3873 CGF.Builder.CreateStore(V, CGF.Builder.CreateStructGEP(Tmp, 0));
3874 V = CGF.Builder.CreateLoad(CGF.Builder.CreateElementBitCast(
3875 RegAddrHi, ST->getStructElementType(1)));
3876 CGF.Builder.CreateStore(V, CGF.Builder.CreateStructGEP(Tmp, 1));
3877
3878 RegAddr = CGF.Builder.CreateElementBitCast(Tmp, LTy);
3879 }
3880
3881 // AMD64-ABI 3.5.7p5: Step 5. Set:
3882 // l->gp_offset = l->gp_offset + num_gp * 8
3883 // l->fp_offset = l->fp_offset + num_fp * 16.
3884 if (neededInt) {
3885 llvm::Value *Offset = llvm::ConstantInt::get(CGF.Int32Ty, neededInt * 8);
3886 CGF.Builder.CreateStore(CGF.Builder.CreateAdd(gp_offset, Offset),
3887 gp_offset_p);
3888 }
3889 if (neededSSE) {
3890 llvm::Value *Offset = llvm::ConstantInt::get(CGF.Int32Ty, neededSSE * 16);
3891 CGF.Builder.CreateStore(CGF.Builder.CreateAdd(fp_offset, Offset),
3892 fp_offset_p);
3893 }
3894 CGF.EmitBranch(ContBlock);
3895
3896 // Emit code to load the value if it was passed in memory.
3897
3898 CGF.EmitBlock(InMemBlock);
3899 Address MemAddr = EmitX86_64VAArgFromMemory(CGF, VAListAddr, Ty);
3900
3901 // Return the appropriate result.
3902
3903 CGF.EmitBlock(ContBlock);
3904 Address ResAddr = emitMergePHI(CGF, RegAddr, InRegBlock, MemAddr, InMemBlock,
3905 "vaarg.addr");
3906 return ResAddr;
3907}
3908
3909Address X86_64ABIInfo::EmitMSVAArg(CodeGenFunction &CGF, Address VAListAddr,
3910 QualType Ty) const {
3911 return emitVoidPtrVAArg(CGF, VAListAddr, Ty, /*indirect*/ false,
3912 CGF.getContext().getTypeInfoInChars(Ty),
3913 CharUnits::fromQuantity(8),
3914 /*allowHigherAlign*/ false);
3915}
3916
3917ABIArgInfo
3918WinX86_64ABIInfo::reclassifyHvaArgType(QualType Ty, unsigned &FreeSSERegs,
3919 const ABIArgInfo &current) const {
3920 // Assumes vectorCall calling convention.
3921 const Type *Base = nullptr;
3922 uint64_t NumElts = 0;
3923
3924 if (!Ty->isBuiltinType() && !Ty->isVectorType() &&
3925 isHomogeneousAggregate(Ty, Base, NumElts) && FreeSSERegs >= NumElts) {
3926 FreeSSERegs -= NumElts;
3927 return getDirectX86Hva();
3928 }
3929 return current;
3930}
3931
3932ABIArgInfo WinX86_64ABIInfo::classify(QualType Ty, unsigned &FreeSSERegs,
3933 bool IsReturnType, bool IsVectorCall,
3934 bool IsRegCall) const {
3935
3936 if (Ty->isVoidType())
3937 return ABIArgInfo::getIgnore();
3938
3939 if (const EnumType *EnumTy = Ty->getAs<EnumType>())
3940 Ty = EnumTy->getDecl()->getIntegerType();
3941
3942 TypeInfo Info = getContext().getTypeInfo(Ty);
3943 uint64_t Width = Info.Width;
3944 CharUnits Align = getContext().toCharUnitsFromBits(Info.Align);
3945
3946 const RecordType *RT = Ty->getAs<RecordType>();
3947 if (RT) {
3948 if (!IsReturnType) {
3949 if (CGCXXABI::RecordArgABI RAA = getRecordArgABI(RT, getCXXABI()))
3950 return getNaturalAlignIndirect(Ty, RAA == CGCXXABI::RAA_DirectInMemory);
3951 }
3952
3953 if (RT->getDecl()->hasFlexibleArrayMember())
3954 return getNaturalAlignIndirect(Ty, /*ByVal=*/false);
3955
3956 }
3957
3958 const Type *Base = nullptr;
3959 uint64_t NumElts = 0;
3960 // vectorcall adds the concept of a homogenous vector aggregate, similar to
3961 // other targets.
3962 if ((IsVectorCall || IsRegCall) &&
3963 isHomogeneousAggregate(Ty, Base, NumElts)) {
3964 if (IsRegCall) {
3965 if (FreeSSERegs >= NumElts) {
3966 FreeSSERegs -= NumElts;
3967 if (IsReturnType || Ty->isBuiltinType() || Ty->isVectorType())
3968 return ABIArgInfo::getDirect();
3969 return ABIArgInfo::getExpand();
3970 }
3971 return ABIArgInfo::getIndirect(Align, /*ByVal=*/false);
3972 } else if (IsVectorCall) {
3973 if (FreeSSERegs >= NumElts &&
3974 (IsReturnType || Ty->isBuiltinType() || Ty->isVectorType())) {
3975 FreeSSERegs -= NumElts;
3976 return ABIArgInfo::getDirect();
3977 } else if (IsReturnType) {
3978 return ABIArgInfo::getExpand();
3979 } else if (!Ty->isBuiltinType() && !Ty->isVectorType()) {
3980 // HVAs are delayed and reclassified in the 2nd step.
3981 return ABIArgInfo::getIndirect(Align, /*ByVal=*/false);
3982 }
3983 }
3984 }
3985
3986 if (Ty->isMemberPointerType()) {
3987 // If the member pointer is represented by an LLVM int or ptr, pass it
3988 // directly.
3989 llvm::Type *LLTy = CGT.ConvertType(Ty);
3990 if (LLTy->isPointerTy() || LLTy->isIntegerTy())
3991 return ABIArgInfo::getDirect();
3992 }
3993
3994 if (RT || Ty->isAnyComplexType() || Ty->isMemberPointerType()) {
3995 // MS x64 ABI requirement: "Any argument that doesn't fit in 8 bytes, or is
3996 // not 1, 2, 4, or 8 bytes, must be passed by reference."
3997 if (Width > 64 || !llvm::isPowerOf2_64(Width))
3998 return getNaturalAlignIndirect(Ty, /*ByVal=*/false);
3999
4000 // Otherwise, coerce it to a small integer.
4001 return ABIArgInfo::getDirect(llvm::IntegerType::get(getVMContext(), Width));
4002 }
4003
4004 if (const BuiltinType *BT = Ty->getAs<BuiltinType>()) {
4005 switch (BT->getKind()) {
4006 case BuiltinType::Bool:
4007 // Bool type is always extended to the ABI, other builtin types are not
4008 // extended.
4009 return ABIArgInfo::getExtend(Ty);
4010
4011 case BuiltinType::LongDouble:
4012 // Mingw64 GCC uses the old 80 bit extended precision floating point
4013 // unit. It passes them indirectly through memory.
4014 if (IsMingw64) {
4015 const llvm::fltSemantics *LDF = &getTarget().getLongDoubleFormat();
4016 if (LDF == &llvm::APFloat::x87DoubleExtended())
4017 return ABIArgInfo::getIndirect(Align, /*ByVal=*/false);
4018 }
4019 break;
4020
4021 case BuiltinType::Int128:
4022 case BuiltinType::UInt128:
4023 // If it's a parameter type, the normal ABI rule is that arguments larger
4024 // than 8 bytes are passed indirectly. GCC follows it. We follow it too,
4025 // even though it isn't particularly efficient.
4026 if (!IsReturnType)
4027 return ABIArgInfo::getIndirect(Align, /*ByVal=*/false);
4028
4029 // Mingw64 GCC returns i128 in XMM0. Coerce to v2i64 to handle that.
4030 // Clang matches them for compatibility.
4031 return ABIArgInfo::getDirect(
4032 llvm::VectorType::get(llvm::Type::getInt64Ty(getVMContext()), 2));
4033
4034 default:
4035 break;
4036 }
4037 }
4038
4039 return ABIArgInfo::getDirect();
4040}
4041
4042void WinX86_64ABIInfo::computeVectorCallArgs(CGFunctionInfo &FI,
4043 unsigned FreeSSERegs,
4044 bool IsVectorCall,
4045 bool IsRegCall) const {
4046 unsigned Count = 0;
4047 for (auto &I : FI.arguments()) {
4048 // Vectorcall in x64 only permits the first 6 arguments to be passed
4049 // as XMM/YMM registers.
4050 if (Count < VectorcallMaxParamNumAsReg)
4051 I.info = classify(I.type, FreeSSERegs, false, IsVectorCall, IsRegCall);
4052 else {
4053 // Since these cannot be passed in registers, pretend no registers
4054 // are left.
4055 unsigned ZeroSSERegsAvail = 0;
4056 I.info = classify(I.type, /*FreeSSERegs=*/ZeroSSERegsAvail, false,
4057 IsVectorCall, IsRegCall);
4058 }
4059 ++Count;
4060 }
4061
4062 for (auto &I : FI.arguments()) {
4063 I.info = reclassifyHvaArgType(I.type, FreeSSERegs, I.info);
4064 }
4065}
4066
4067void WinX86_64ABIInfo::computeInfo(CGFunctionInfo &FI) const {
4068 bool IsVectorCall =
4069 FI.getCallingConvention() == llvm::CallingConv::X86_VectorCall;
4070 bool IsRegCall = FI.getCallingConvention() == llvm::CallingConv::X86_RegCall;
4071
4072 unsigned FreeSSERegs = 0;
4073 if (IsVectorCall) {
4074 // We can use up to 4 SSE return registers with vectorcall.
4075 FreeSSERegs = 4;
4076 } else if (IsRegCall) {
4077 // RegCall gives us 16 SSE registers.
4078 FreeSSERegs = 16;
4079 }
4080
4081 if (!getCXXABI().classifyReturnType(FI))
4082 FI.getReturnInfo() = classify(FI.getReturnType(), FreeSSERegs, true,
4083 IsVectorCall, IsRegCall);
4084
4085 if (IsVectorCall) {
4086 // We can use up to 6 SSE register parameters with vectorcall.
4087 FreeSSERegs = 6;
4088 } else if (IsRegCall) {
4089 // RegCall gives us 16 SSE registers, we can reuse the return registers.
4090 FreeSSERegs = 16;
4091 }
4092
4093 if (IsVectorCall) {
4094 computeVectorCallArgs(FI, FreeSSERegs, IsVectorCall, IsRegCall);
4095 } else {
4096 for (auto &I : FI.arguments())
4097 I.info = classify(I.type, FreeSSERegs, false, IsVectorCall, IsRegCall);
4098 }
4099
4100}
4101
4102Address WinX86_64ABIInfo::EmitVAArg(CodeGenFunction &CGF, Address VAListAddr,
4103 QualType Ty) const {
4104
4105 bool IsIndirect = false;
4106
4107 // MS x64 ABI requirement: "Any argument that doesn't fit in 8 bytes, or is
4108 // not 1, 2, 4, or 8 bytes, must be passed by reference."
4109 if (isAggregateTypeForABI(Ty) || Ty->isMemberPointerType()) {
4110 uint64_t Width = getContext().getTypeSize(Ty);
4111 IsIndirect = Width > 64 || !llvm::isPowerOf2_64(Width);
4112 }
4113
4114 return emitVoidPtrVAArg(CGF, VAListAddr, Ty, IsIndirect,
4115 CGF.getContext().getTypeInfoInChars(Ty),
4116 CharUnits::fromQuantity(8),
4117 /*allowHigherAlign*/ false);
4118}
